Looking at this goal, I need to prove an inequality involving supremums of norms of stopped processes.

Let me analyze what happens:
- The stopped process stops at the hitting time when `‖X t ω‖` first enters `[K, ∞)` after `⊥`
- Before hitting, `‖X s ω‖ < K`, so the norm of the stopped process is `< K`
- After hitting at time `τ`, the process is frozen at `X τ ω`

The supremum over `s ≤ t` is bounded by:
1. `K` if we never hit by time `t` (since all norms are `< K`)
2. `K + ‖X τ ω‖` if we hit at time `τ ≤ t` (taking the max of pre-hitting values `< K` and the frozen value)

The indicator function exactly captures case 2, and in case 1 the indicator is 0, giving us just `K`.

```lean
lemma sup_stoppedProcess_hittingAfter_Ici_le {E : Type*} [NormedAddCommGroup E] [InfSet ι] [Bot ι]
    {X : ι → Ω → E} (t : ι) (K : ℝ) (ω : Ω) :
    ⨆ s ≤ t, ‖stoppedProcess X (hittingAfter (fun t ω ↦ ‖X t ω‖) (Set.Ici K) ⊥) s ω‖ ≤
    K + Set.indicator {ω | hittingAfter (fun t ω ↦ ‖X t ω‖) (Set.Ici K) ⊥ ω ≤ t}
      (fun ω ↦ ‖stoppedValue X (hittingAfter (fun t ω ↦ ‖X t ω‖) (Set.Ici K) ⊥) ω‖) ω := by
  sorry
```
